# Garde-robe

Personal wardrobe manager. Stack: Next.js App Router, Supabase (auth/DB/storage), Vercel, TypeScript.

Product docs:
- `docs/product.md` — vision and user flows
- `docs/v1-scope.md` — MVP boundaries
- `docs/roadmap.md` — milestone order

## Agent Workflow

- Propose a short implementation plan before writing code.
- Only change files necessary for the requested task.
- Do not make large refactors unless explicitly requested.
- Ask for confirmation before introducing a new npm dependency.
- After implementing, provide a short manual test checklist (see template below).

## Code Quality

- Use TypeScript strictly — avoid `any`; prefer explicit types on public APIs.
- Keep components small and modular — one responsibility per component.
- Keep business logic out of UI components — use `lib/`, hooks, or server actions.
- Prefer simple, maintainable solutions over clever abstractions.

Folder conventions:
- `app/` — routes, layouts, server components
- `components/` — presentational and small composed UI
- `lib/` — Supabase clients, data access, domain logic
- `hooks/` — reusable client-side logic

## Documentation

- When adding a feature, update relevant files in `docs/`.
- Document new or changed environment variables in `.env.example` and explain them in the implementation summary.

## Secrets and Environment Variables

Never expose secret keys in client-side code.

| Variable | Where | Notes |
|----------|-------|-------|
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` | Client + server | Public |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` | Client + server | Public; RLS protects data |
| `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` | Server only | Never in client bundles; future use |

- Frontend uses `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` env vars only for Supabase.
- Server-only operations (admin, bypass RLS) belong in server components, route handlers, or server actions — never in `"use client"` files.

## Next.js App Router

- Use `app/` directory; server components by default.
- Client components only when needed (interactivity, hooks, browser APIs).
- Colocate route-specific code under `app/`.

## Supabase

- Use `@supabase/ssr` for cookie-based auth in Next.js.
- Enable RLS on all user tables; never rely on client-side filtering for security.
- Storage buckets use user-scoped paths (e.g. `{userId}/{itemId}`).

## Vercel

- Configure env vars in the Vercel dashboard; mirror them in `.env.example`.
- Avoid Vercel-specific hacks that break local development.

## UI

- Mobile-first responsive design (Tailwind: base → `sm` → `md` → `lg`).
- Clean, minimal, fashion-oriented interface — generous whitespace, neutral palette, photography-forward item cards.
- Prioritize visual browsing over dense tables or cluttered dashboards.

## Future Outfit Canvas

Prepare structure without building canvas before milestone 5:
- `components/canvas/` — canvas UI (stub until M5)
- `lib/types/outfit.ts` — shared types for item position and scale
- Reusable item components for list and canvas sidebar (e.g. `ItemThumbnail`)
- Avoid list-only layouts that block drag-and-drop reuse

## Manual Test Checklist Template

End every feature implementation with:

```
## Manual test checklist
- [ ] Sign in / sign out (if auth touched)
- [ ] Core happy path for the feature
- [ ] Mobile viewport (375px)
- [ ] Desktop viewport
- [ ] Error/empty states
```
